Rating: 4
There is such a better way of making this dish. Not real time consuming, but a little more complex of a dish that is worth the effort for the flavor. Don't cook the meat in just the broth; I roughly chopped a couple of medium sized yellow onions, thru in two whole jalapeno peppers and about ten garlic cloves or to taste, and some adobo paste, 3 lbs. of cubed boneless pork chops and let that simmer for an hour or so. Let the meat sit in the broth for a day or two and then discard the garlic cloves, jalapenos and juice. The onions should have mostly melted away and don't worry about discarding remains of onion. Lightly grease a cast iron skillet or any frying pan that you can put into the oven with whatever oil or lard you may like. Take the drained pork meat w/o garlic cloves or pepper and brown the pork meat to your liking; add a good amount of orange juice, yes, orange juice and several packages of Goya Sazon seasoning w/o Annatto, stir well and put pan into a 400 degree oven. Check and stir about every 10-15 minutes to keep all juices incorporated with the meat and reduces over browning of meat. When all liquid has reduced, serve with flour tortillas, quacamole, and your favorite red tomatoe pico salsa and sour cream if desired. I also love putting the pork meat into the flour tortilla, topping it with the pico salsa and some "Enchilada Cheese" that is made by Casique, a Mexican cheese vendor. A little quacamole only on the side not incorporated with the meat, cheese and tortilla. I love the flavor of the meat, cheese, salsa, and tortilla only. The meat freezes very well if you store the meat properly. I have a vacumn sealer and have pulled a package of this pork meat out of the freezer a year later, and it is great!!!! Just like what I got in Cabo San Lucas last year but a little better, because I didn't have to pay the airfare to Cabo!

